human social behavior and horse handling ushered in by elite riding houses such as Angelo's Academy and Mr. Carter's; and the public perception of equestrian endeavors, from performances at places such as Astley's Amphitheatre to the satire of Henry William Bunbury. Throughout, Mattfeld shows how horses aided the performance of idealized masculinity among communities of riders, in turn influencing how men were perceived in regard to status, reputation, and gender.Drawing on human-animal studies, gender studies, and historical studies, Becoming Centaur offers a new account of masculinity that reaches beyond anthropocentrism to consider the role of animals in shaping man.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aHorsemanshipxHistoryx18th centuryxEngland. 0aHorsemanshipzEnglandxHistoryy18th century. 0aHorsemen and horsewomenxHistoryx18th centuryxEngland. 0aHorsemen and horsewomenzEnglandxHistoryy18th century. 0aHuman-animal relationshipsxHistoryx18th centuryxEngland. 0aHuman-animal relationshipszEnglandxHistoryy18th century. 0aMasculinityxHistoryx18th centuryxEnglandxEnglandxHistory. 0aMasculinityzEnglandxHistoryy18th century. 7aHISTORY / Modern / 18th Century.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn State University Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311074524540uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780271079745zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780271079745423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780271079745.jpg  a978-3-11-074524-5  Penn State University Press Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK